<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10042c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10042c">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10042c"> 42(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> span. forefinger of R</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>The Open Forum</b> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The Claddagh Ring. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It was not originally Irish, but was brought by the sailors of the Armada <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> These <mark>Spanish</mark> sailors married into the community, impressing them with many of their customs <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> They elected a chief, whom they called &ldquo;The King of the Claddagh,&rdquo; and on his marriage he was to present his bride with one of these beautiful rings, hailing her as &ldquo;The Queen of the Claddagh.&rdquo; It subsequently became permitted for other women of the community to wear this pattern of ring as wedding ring <mark>on the fore finger of the right hand</mark> until now, when it is a general custom. <small> <a name="CT12apr24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CT12apr24"><cite title="source">Connacht Tribune</cite></a> (12 April 1924) 7/5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
